ce:section.ce:para:
In summary, in the synthsis of C-dots from PEGs, the reactions mainly went through an “oxidized decomposition – crosslinking – carbonization” process (
                        Scheme 1
                        ). For the oxidized decomposition to occur, a certain threshold of temperature and reaction duration was required, which was closely related to the M.W. of PEG used: for PEG with low M.W. (i.e., PEG400), relatively low temperature and short reaction time could trigger the sequence for C-dots formation; and elevated temperature and prolonged reaction tend to over carbonize C-dots and thus reduce their fluorescence (Fig. 2a). On the other hand, for PEG with large M.W. (i.e., PEG4000), relatively high temperature and long reaction time would be required to trigger the oxidized decomposition and the following C-dots formation; if the temperature was low and reaction time was short, there may be no C-dots formed (Fig. 2d). Since reaction temperature and time had distinct effects for reactions of PEGs with different M.W., the temperature and time should be carefully and individually optimized when PEGs of different M.W. were applied as carbon precursors for the synthesis of C-dots.
